		<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-36980">
				<div id="div-comment-36980" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/bdb6a254717e0278bcd9926e48bedbc4?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />		<cite class="fn"><a href='http://clothesaholic.blogspot.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>gidgetbananas</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.amateurgourmet.com/2008/12/the_noknead_bre.html#comment-36980">
			December 29, 2008 at 7:30 pm</a>		</div>

		<p>Gawd, I love no knead bread.  If you don&#8217;t like the flavor, it&#8217;s simple enough to jazz up the recipe.  I use a mixture of whole wheat and unbleach bread flour, with a little more salt and crushed rosemary, for a savory bread.  I add 1/4 cup sugar and dried cranberries to make a sweeter breakfast bread. (Note that sugar causes the bread to rise like crazy.)</p>
<p>You don&#8217;t need an expensive Le Crueset dutch oven to cook it in.  Covered Pyrex ovenwear works just fine, and I&#8217;m sure a cast iron dutch oven would work fine too.</p>
<p>Experiment!  This recipe is practically fail-proof!</p>

		<div class="reply">
				</div>
				</div>
		</li>
